Lifting the iron curtain of vision.

Rosin B(1), Sahel JA(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Ophthalmology/UPMC Eye Center, University of Pittsburgh, 
Pittsburgh, PA, USA.

Comment on
    EMBO Mol Med. 2023 Feb 8;15(2):e16525.

Ocular and specifically retinal toxicities of systemic medications are prevalent 
and encompass many disease modalities. For many of these pharmaceuticals, 
established follow-up protocols are in place to ensure timely detection and 
cessation of therapy. However, while for some disorders, cessation of therapy is 
a viable option due to existing treatment alternatives, for some others 
cessation of treatment can be life threatening and/or shorten the patient's life 
expectancy. Such is the case for iron chelating agents used in 
transfusion-dependent patients of Thalassemia, of which deferoxamine (DFO) is 
the most widely used. In their recent article in EMBO Molecular Medicine, Kong 
et al (2023) addressed the issue of DFO-induced retinal toxicity used both 
in vivo and in vitro techniques. Their study suggests a potentially protective 
role for α-ketoglutarate (AKG) supplementation against DFO toxicity.

